## 5.1 Pharmacodynamic properties

Pharmacotherapeutic group: Angiotensin II Antagonists, plain, {{ drug.molecular_formula }} code: {{ drug.atc_code }}.

Mechanism of action

{{ drug.name }} is an orally active and specific angiotensin II receptor (type AT1) antagonist.

{{ drug.name }} displaces angiotensin II with very high affinity from its binding site at the AT1 receptor subtype, which is responsible for the known actions of angiotensin II. {{ drug.name }} does not exhibit any partial agonist activity at the AT1 receptor. {{ drug.name }} selectively binds the AT1 receptor. The binding is long-lasting. {{ drug.name }} does not show affinity for other receptors, including AT2and other less characterised AT receptors. The functional role of these receptors is not known, nor is the effect of their possible overstimulation by angiotensin II, whose levels are increased by {{ drug.name }}.

Plasma aldosterone levels are decreased by {{ drug.name }}. {{ drug.name }} does not inhibit human plasma renin or block ion channels. {{ drug.name }} does not inhibit angiotensin converting enzyme (kininase II), the enzyme which also degrades bradykinin. Therefore it is not expected to potentiate bradykinin-mediated adverse effects.

In human, an {{ drug.strength }} dose of {{ drug.name }} almost completely inhibits the angiotensin II evoked blood pressure increase. The inhibitory effect is maintained over 24 hours and still measurable up to 48 hours.

Clinical efficacy and safety

Treatment of essential hypertension

After the first dose of {{ drug.name }}, the antihypertensive activity gradually becomes evident within 3 hours. The maximum reduction in blood pressure is generally attained 4 to 8 weeks after the start of treatment and is sustained during long-term therapy.

The antihypertensive effect persists constantly over 24 hours after dosing and includes the last 4 hours before the next dose as shown by ambulatory blood pressure measurements. This is confirmed by trough to peak ratios consistently above 80% seen after doses of 40 and {{ drug.strength }} of {{ drug.name }} in placebo controlled clinical studies.

There is an apparent trend to a dose relationship to a time to recovery of baseline systolic blood pressure ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}). In this respect data concerning diastolic blood pressure ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) are inconsistent.

In patients with hypertension {{ drug.name }} reduces both systolic and diastolic blood pressure without affecting pulse rate. The contribution of the medicinal product's diuretic and natriuretic effect to its hypotensive activity has still to be defined. The antihypertensive efficacy of {{ drug.name }} is comparable to that of agents representative of other classes of antihypertensive medicinal products (demonstrated in clinical trials comparing {{ drug.name }} to amlodipine, atenolol, enalapril, hydrochlorothiazide, and lisinopril).

Upon abrupt cessation of treatment with {{ drug.name }}, blood pressure gradually returns to pre-treatment values over a period of several days without evidence of rebound hypertension.

The incidence of dry cough was significantly lower in patients treated with {{ drug.name }} than in those given angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors in clinical trials directly comparing the two antihypertensive treatments.

Cardiovascular prevention

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} (Ongoing {{ drug.name }} Alone and in Combination with Ramipril Global Endpoint Trial) compared the effects of {{ drug.name }}, ramipril and the combination of {{ drug.name }} and ramipril on cardiovascular outcomes in 25620 patients aged 55 years or older with a history of coronary artery disease, stroke, {{ drug.molecular_formula }}, peripheral arterial disease, or type 2 diabetes mellitus accompanied by evidence of end-organ damage (e.g. retinopathy, left ventricular hypertrophy, macro- or microalbuminuria), which is a population at risk for cardiovascular events.

Patients were randomized to one of the three following treatment groups: {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }} (n = 8542), ramipril {{ drug.strength }} (n = 8576), or the combination of {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }} plus ramipril {{ drug.strength }} (n = 8502), and followed for a mean observation time of 4.5 years.

{{ drug.name }} showed a similar effect to ramipril in reducing the primary composite endpoint of cardiovascular death, non-fatal myocardial infarction, non-fatal stroke, or hospitalization for congestive heart failure. The incidence of the primary endpoint was similar in the {{ drug.name }} (16.7%) and ramipril (16.5%) groups. The hazard ratio for {{ drug.name }} vs. ramipril was 1.01 (97.5% CI 0.93 - 1.10, p (non-inferiority) = 0.0019 at a margin of 1.13). The all-cause mortality rate was 11.6 % and 11.8 % among {{ drug.name }} and ramipril treated patients, respectively.

{{ drug.name }} was found to be similarly effective to ramipril in the pre-specified secondary endpoint of cardiovascular death, non-fatal myocardial infarction, and non-fatal stroke [0.99 (97.5% CI 0.90 - 1.08), p (non-inferiority) = 0.0004], the primary endpoint in the reference study {{ drug.molecular_formula }} (The Heart Outcomes Prevention Evaluation Study), which had investigated the effect of ramipril vs. placebo.

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} randomized {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-I intolerant patients with otherwise similar inclusion criteria as {{ drug.molecular_formula }} to {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }} (n = 2954) or placebo (n = 2972), both given on top of standard care. The mean duration of follow up was 4 years and 8 months. No statistically significant difference in the incidence of the primary composite endpoint (cardiovascular death, non-fatal myocardial infarction, non-fatal stroke, or hospitalization for congestive heart failure) was found [15.7% in the {{ drug.name }} and 17.0% in the placebo groups with a hazard ratio of 0.92 (95% CI 0.81-1.05, p = 0.22)]. There was evidence for a benefit of {{ drug.name }} compared to placebo in the pre-specified secondary composite endpoint of cardiovascular death, non-fatal myocardial infarction, and non-fatal stroke [0.87 (95% CI 0.76-1.00, p = 0.048)], There was no evidence for benefit on cardiovascular mortality (hazard ratio 1.03, 95% CI 0.85-1.24).

Two large randomised, controlled trials ({{ drug.molecular_formula }} (ONgoing {{ drug.name }} Alone and in combination with Ramipril Global Endpoint Trial) and VA {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-D (The Veterans Affairs Nephropathy in Diabetes)) have examined the use of the combination of an {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-inhibitor with an angiotensin II receptor blocker.

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} was a study conducted in patients with a history of cardiovascular or cerebrovascular disease, or type 2 diabetes mellitus accompanied by evidence of end-organ damage. VA {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-D was a study in patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus and diabetic nephropathy.

These studies have shown no significant beneficial effect on renal and/or cardiovascular outcomes and mortality, while an increased risk of Hyperkalaemia, acute kidney injury and/or hypotension as compared to monotherapy was observed. Given their similar pharmacodynamic properties, these results are also relevant for other {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-inhibitors and angiotensin II receptor blockers.

{{ drug.molecular_formula }}-inhibitors and angiotensin II receptor blockers should therefore not be used concomitantly in patients with diabetic nephropathy.

{{ drug.molecular_formula }} (Aliskiren Trial in Type 2 Diabetes Using Cardiovascular and Renal Disease Endpoints) was a study designed to test the benefit of adding aliskiren to a standard therapy of an {{ drug.molecular_formula }}-inhibitor or an angiotensin II receptor blocker in patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus and chronic kidney disease, cardiovascular disease, or both. The study was terminated early because of an increased risk of adverse outcomes. Cardiovascular death and stroke were both numerically more frequent in the aliskiren group than in the placebo group and adverse events and serious adverse events of interest (Hyperkalaemia, hypotension and renal dysfunction) were more frequently reported in the aliskiren group than in the placebo group.

Cough and angioedema were less frequently reported in patients treated with {{ drug.name }} than in patients treated with ramipril, whereas hypotension was more frequently reported with {{ drug.name }}.

Combining {{ drug.name }} with ramipril did not add further benefit over ramipril or {{ drug.name }} alone. CV mortality and all cause mortality were numerically higher with the combination. In addition, there was a significantly higher incidence of Hyperkalaemia, renal failure, hypotension and syncope in the combination arm. Therefore the use of a combination of {{ drug.name }} and ramipril is not recommended in this population.

In the "Prevention Regimen For Effectively avoiding Second Strokes" ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) trial in patients 50 years and older, who recently experienced stroke, an increased incidence of sepsis was noted for {{ drug.name }} compared with placebo, 0.70% vs. 0.49% [RR 1.43 (95% confidence interval 1.00- 2.06)]; the incidence of fatal sepsis cases was increased for patients taking {{ drug.name }} (0.33%) vs. patients taking placebo (0.16%) [RR 2.07 (95% confidence interval 1.14 3.76)]. The observed increased occurrence rate of sepsis associated with the use of {{ drug.name }} may be either a chance finding or related to a mechanism not currently known.

Paediatric population

The safety and efficacy of {{ drug.name }} in children and adolescents aged below 18 years have not been established.

The blood pressure lowering effects of two doses of {{ drug.name }} were assessed in 76 hypertensive, largely overweight patients aged 6 to < 18 years (body weight ≥ 20 kg and ≤ 120 kg, mean 74.6 kg), after taking {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }}/kg (n = 29 treated) or {{ drug.strength }}/kg (n = 31 treated) over a four-week treatment period. By inclusion the presence of secondary hypertension was not investigated. In some of the investigated patients the doses used were higher than those recommended in the treatment of hypertension in the adult population, reaching a daily dose comparable to160 mg, which was tested in adults. After adjustment for age group effects mean {{ drug.molecular_formula }} changes from baseline (primary objective) were -14.5 (1.7) mm Hg in the {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }}/kg group, -9.7 (1.7) mm Hg in the {{ drug.name }} {{ drug.strength }}/kg group, and -6.0 (2.4) in the placebo group. The adjusted {{ drug.molecular_formula }} changes from baseline were -8.4 (1.5) mm Hg, -4.5 (1.6) mm Hg and -3.5 (2.1) mm Hg respectively. The change was dose dependent. The safety data from this study in patients aged 6 to < 18 years appeared generally similar to that observed in adults. The safety of long term treatment of {{ drug.name }} in children and adolescents was not evaluated.

An increase in eosinophils reported in this patient population has not been recorded in adults. Its clinical significance and relevance is unknown.

These clinical data do not allow to make conclusions on the efficacy and safety of {{ drug.name }} in hypertensive paediatric population.
